tda_expert.interpretation: Treat both tables as encounter-level data linked by patient and appointment identifiers. Use patient_no/pt_id as the primary join, and appointment_id/appt_id as a secondary join when available to ensure 1:1 encounter alignment.
Use doctors as the provider dimension and appointments as fact/encounter records. Join on physician_id/doctor_id to attach provider attributes to each appointment.

Align appointments with claims at the encounter level via the patient identifier. Use patient_no/member_id as the main join key; consider adding a composite key with date/time or other encounter attributes in a later refinement step if available.
Use patients as the core patient dimension and appointments as patient-related events. Join on patient_no/patient_id as a strict FK→PK relationship.
Model departments as an organizational dimension and doctors as provider entities linked to departments. Join on department_id/dept_code to attach department attributes to each doctor.
Treat diagnoses and insurance_claims as encounter/claim-level data tied through the patient identifier. Join on pt_id/member_id to associate clinical diagnoses with financial claim records.
Use patients as the patient dimension and diagnoses as patient-level clinical events. Join on pt_id/patient_id as a FK→PK relationship.
Link claims to the patient dimension using member_id/patient_id. This supports patient-centric views of financial/utilization data.
Treat medications as a medication master/dimension and prescriptions as transactional records referencing that master. Join on medication_id/med_code.

business_insights.title: [healthcare] High Average Billed Amount
business_insights.description: The average billed amount of $6,770.45 is significantly high, indicating potential issues with pricing strategies or patient affordability.
business_insights.business_impact: High billed amounts may deter patients from seeking necessary care, impacting overall patient volume and revenue.

business_insights.title: [healthcare] Inefficient Appointment Duration Management
business_insights.description: The average appointment duration is 44.43 minutes, with a significant number of appointments scheduled for 30 minutes, which may lead to rushed consultations.
recommendations: Consider increasing time slots for complex cases
business_insights.business_impact: Rushed appointments can negatively impact patient satisfaction and care quality, leading to potential loss of patients.

business_insights.title: [healthcare] Severity of Diagnoses
business_insights.description: The severity distribution shows 6 severe diagnoses, which may indicate a need for enhanced care protocols for high-risk patients.
recommendations: Implement targeted care plans for severe cases
business_insights.business_impact: Addressing severe cases effectively can improve patient outcomes and reduce readmissions.

business_insights.title: Pending Status
business_insights.description: Found 2 records (9.1%) with 'pending' status in insurance_claims

business_insights.title: [healthcare] Potential Over-Reliance on Specific Insurance Providers
business_insights.description: The data shows a concentration of claims from Aetna (6 claims) and BlueCross (5 claims), indicating a risk of over-reliance on these providers.
business_insights.business_impact: Over-reliance on a few providers can lead to financial instability if those relationships change.

business_insights.title: [healthcare] High Appointment Completion Rate
business_insights.description: With 30 out of 35 appointments completed, the completion rate is approximately 86%, which is a positive indicator of operational efficiency.
recommendations: Monitor for any changes in patient attendance
business_insights.business_impact: A high completion rate suggests effective patient engagement and scheduling, contributing to stable revenue.

business_insights.title: [healthcare] High Average Billed Amount
business_insights.description: The average billed amount for insurance claims is $6770.45, which is significantly high compared to typical healthcare services. This could indicate overcharging or a need for better cost management.
recommendations: Conduct a market analysis for competitive pricing
business_insights.business_impact: Potential loss of patients due to high costs and increased scrutiny from insurance providers.

business_insights.title: [healthcare] Concentration in Insurance Providers
business_insights.description: The dataset shows a concentration of claims from three main insurance providers: Aetna, BlueCross, and Medicare. This reliance on a limited number of insurers poses a risk if any of them change their reimbursement policies.
recommendations: Diversify partnerships with more insurance providers
business_insights.business_impact: Reducing dependency on a few insurers can stabilize revenue streams and mitigate financial risks.
